HE DEMOCRATIZATION OF THE IMAGE-BASED SCREENING PLATFORMS is a reality for pharmaceutical companies as well

as research institutes. The recent usage of these fully automated systems allows identification of active molecules without the constraint of repetitive or inaccurate intensive manual labor. Such method is used increasingly for primary screening, target identification, and lead generations. High-resolution microscopes, combined with the specificity of fluorescent probes for labeling targets of interest, provide accurate determination of protein localization and valuable information for understanding the molecular mechanisms that underlie the cell functions. However, an accurate spatial localization of fluorescent signals can be challenging as biological
